    {
      "id": "91073f8242a23e02c783ff110e2e35d3df39f013",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-12 16:56:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\n(2 comments)\n\nApproach looks reasonable, though Alex is much more familiar with lu_cache than I am. \n\nIf think we want to have the minimum lu_cache size for ZFS to be at least the number of service threads + number of OIs to avoid thrashing the cache.\n\nI also wonder if the lu_cache size for ldiskfs should be reigned in as well?  Considering the lu_cache itself is only a fraction  of the amount of memory that is actually being pinned by each object (inode or dnode, block buffer, etc) then even 20% of memory is too large and it will never be purged by itself.\n\nIs there a callback from the VM to shrink the lu_cache to keep it in check?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "1b08dcef79e8a70bebca5dbec24f224832f178fd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-16 14:45:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nthe more I think about this, the more I like the approach. missing lu_object won't result in disk I/O immediately, though will result in OI lookup, additional cache lookups, etc. but in general I'd think this should work well with ldiskfs too - in the end lu-object cache Lustre state, not on-disk state. for frequently used objects we'll have Lustre state cached (including expensive SA handles).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2ea9ab6bee2ec4a4a93b028bd1c234ead1ca88af",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 192,
        "name": "Brian Behlendorf",
        "email": "behlendorf1@llnl.gov",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-06-16 18:44:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAndreas, Alex.  Aside from the style issues, how would you like me to refresh this patch so it can be merged?  I like the idea of doing the same thing for ldiskfs and zfs but I was reluctant to limit the cache for ldiskfs without data showing the impact of this change.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5c2c8fbc5c0b21d5181220da94c1e4ef8cebac08",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-17 00:33:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI think this patch has a reasonable chance to land for 2.6.0 if it is making such a critical improvement to ZFS performance as you say. Since we've been testing ldiskfs without this change and haven't seen the same memory problems I think the change to reduce the lu_cache for ldiskfs should wait until 2.7. \n\nI've added Oleg to the CC list to see what he thinks of landing this patch for 2.6.0.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "21d4e6be75e866c3649c2444afe3a8999fc67e18",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-06-17 00:35:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "1a7c12e4a9fa9da6eccc0c5b6dad14c650daa78c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-17 17:21:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nBrian, is this patch already running at LLNL?  I'd feel a lot better landing this for the upcoming 2.6.0 if this has already been in use on Sequoia.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "c665b569db3b26b727d4f0ce9698a9998c8a4964",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 192,
        "name": "Brian Behlendorf",
        "email": "behlendorf1@llnl.gov",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-06-17 17:56:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nYes this patch started rolling out along with the latest ZFS code a week or so ago.  Thus far it's been working nicely but as I mentioned in the issue we don't really have any before and after numbers to compare.  Although it would be pretty straight forward to get some if someone has the time.\n\nIt hasn't rolled out to the Sequoia filesystem yet but it is on several others.  At this point we've retired all of our ldiskfs based filesystems and have I believe 8 zfs based ones in production or various sizes and configurations.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
